From 410bab18e30d9bdd56faf7434b304c00b2b47194 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
Date: Tue, 10 Mar 2026 13:05:20 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 24/N] XFAIL tests that fail due to Cygwin/MSYS2 platform
 limitations

Cygwin (and therefore MSYS2, which defines __CYGWIN__ and reports
sys.platform == 'cygwin') identifies as a POSIX system, but lacks
full POSIX semantics in several areas.  A total of 45 tests across
both the C test suite and the Python cmdline test suite fail because
of three distinct platform limitations:

1. Legacy charset conversion (4 C-level tests, 4 Python tests):
   Cygwin's locale subsystem does not support iconv conversions
   between legacy single-byte encodings (Latin-1/ISO-8859-1) and
   UTF-8.  Subversion's UTF-8 conversion layer reports "Non-ASCII
   character detected, and unable to convert to/from UTF-8".  This
   affects subst_translate-test 1-2 and utf-test 3-4, which are
   guarded with #ifdef __CYGWIN__ to use SVN_TEST_XFAIL2 instead of
   SVN_TEST_PASS2.  The same limitation also affects prop_tests 22
   (invalid property name handling triggers the same conversion
   path), prop_tests 41-42 (svn:author with non-ASCII chars), and
   svnsync_tests 24 (re-encoding non-UTF-8 svn:* props).

2. Executable-bit semantics (8 Python tests): Cygwin passes the
   is_posix_os() check so these tests are not skipped, but setting
   svn:executable does not actually change a file's POSIX permission
   bits on Cygwin's emulated filesystem layer.  This affects
   import_tests 1, copy_tests 10, lock_tests 25-26,
   merge_tests 116, schedule_tests 4 (both add and revert variants),
   and revert_tests 24 (permission-only reverts).

3. Symlink handling (25 Python tests): Cygwin's symlink emulation
   does not fully match real POSIX symlink behavior.  This affects
   the bulk of special_tests (1, 3, 5, 7-10, 13, 15, 17-18, 21-23,
   25), copy_tests 84, diff_tests 75 and 88, merge_tests 81,
   merge_reintegrate_tests 19, svnadmin_tests 22, stat_tests 6,
   patch_tests 30, 41, 55-56, 70, 72, and wc_tests 7.

All of these are well-understood platform limitations, not subversion
bugs.  The underlying functionality works correctly on Linux (glibc
iconv, real POSIX permissions, native symlinks) and native Windows
(Win32 APIs, no POSIX emulation).

Marking the tests as XFAIL rather than skipping them means they still
execute on every run.  If Cygwin's emulation ever improves enough for
any of these to start passing, the test framework will report XPASS
(unexpected pass), drawing attention to the fact that the XFAIL
annotation can be removed.

For the Python tests, the existing svntest.main.is_os_cygwin predicate
is used as the XFail condition, which is already employed elsewhere
(e.g. case_only_rename in copy_tests.py).  For the C tests, #ifdef
__CYGWIN__ guards select between SVN_TEST_XFAIL2 and SVN_TEST_PASS2 in
the test descriptor arrays, making the change a strict no-op on all
other platforms.

Additionally, special_tests 27 (multiline_symlink_special) had a
pre-existing @XFail(svntest.main.is_posix_os) that caused an XPASS on
Cygwin because the test happens to pass there.  The condition is
narrowed to exclude Cygwin so the test is expected to pass on Cygwin
(where it does) while remaining XFAIL on other POSIX systems.

